<TITLE> Shamsul, Anwar, 4 more get HC bail </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Aug 25 (bdnews24.com)  Former BNP ministers M Shamsul Islam and MK Anwar, former state minister Barkatullah Bulu, former deputy minister Asadul Habib Dulu and two others secured bail in different cases from the High Court on Monday. The HC also put freezes on the proceedings of two separate corruption cases against former minister Mirza Abbas and state minister Lutfozzaman Babar. A High Court bench led by Justice Sharifuddin Chaklader granted ad interim bail to M Shamsul Islam and MK Anwar until charge framing in the Barapukuria coalmine case. The court also asked the government and the Anticorruption Commission to show cause as to why they would not be given permanent bail in the case. The ACC filed a case with Shahbag Police Station on Feb 26 against 16 people, including Khaleda Zia and 10 former ministers, on charges of irregularities and corruption in running the coalmine. A HC bench of justices Sharifuddin Chaklader and Md Imdadul Huq Azad also granted six-month bail to controversial businessman Giasuddin Al Mamun Monday in four extortion cases and the Niko graft case. A bench led by Justice Sharifuddin Chaklader granted anticipatory bail to former whip Moshiur Rahman in a murder case. The same bench granted anticipatory bail to Barkatullah Bulu in an illegal wealth case till submission of the police report. The bench also ordered the government to show cause as to why he should not be granted permanent anticipatory bail. The same HC bench granted anticipatory bail to Asadul Habib Dulu in an extortion case. A bench led by Sharifuddin Chaklader also put a freeze on the proceedings of a case against Babar, filed for amassing illegal wealth, for three months. The ruling that stayed proceedings of the corruption case against Mirza Abbas for three months came from the bench of justices Khademul Islam Chowdhury and Mashuk Hossain Ahmed. The bench also issued a rule nisi to the government and the Anticorruption Commission to explain within four weeks to explain why the case would not be declared illegal. bdnews24
